    <item>
      <label xml:lang="en">Business</label>
      <documentation xml:lang="en">This is an example of "v2" metamodel support PoC code for Archi.
We have a metamodel here, which defines how things should be interrelated.
From the metamodel, a policy file is generated, which captures the ontology defined by the metamodel.
The objects of the model are identified and their respective attributes are then filled in, resulting in tables of objects. This is done in export time now. It will be done in runtime in a non-PoC implementation.
There is also preliminary policy support: the policy also defines what kind of relationships are possible/mandatory. As the metamodel is not tuned for this yet, and the PoC uses the v1 Rich Export logic, it is not exactly working as expected. See the styled export log to get a feeling however.</documentation>
      <item>
        <label xml:lang="en">repository of servers and systems</label>
        <documentation xml:lang="en">See &lt;a href="objectlist.html#Server"&gt;the Server list&lt;/a&gt;, the &lt;a href="objectlist.html#Application"&gt;the Application list&lt;/a&gt;, and the &lt;a href="objectlist.html#ApplicationCollection"&gt;The ApplicationCollection list&lt;/a&gt;.
For the details, see the section about metamodels. 
On Monday, 31 January 2011 23:26:06 UTC+1, TerChris wrote:

    Hi
    First of all I’m pleased to find a tool that I think will help me in creating a repository of servers, systems and the dependencies between them.
    I was on a project earlier where we used www.troux.com Architect (ver8). Troux Architect is not a cheap tool and we cannot justify the cost of it on the project I’m working at now.
    I want to do the same as I did in the “troux-project”. That is to create a repository of all servers, systems, dependencies and the people responsible for running/administering/developing each item.

    I want to model this structure.
    Server attributes:
    PhysicalHardware (eg the physical server)
    Location (where the PhysicalHardware is placed)
    ServerName (the name of the server)
    IP Address
    Status (In preparation, In Test, In production, Under liquidation, Liquidated)
    NetworkZone (what network zone the server is placed)
    OperatingSystem (what OS it runs)
    ServerRole (Application server, File Server…)
    TechnicalContact (Name of person)

    Application attributes: (a application or system)
    ApplicationName (name of the system)
    TechnicalContact (Name of person)
    AdmContact (Name of person)

    Application collection: (A collection of applications/systems that belong together eg Sallary payment)
    CollectionName (name of the collection of applications)
    AdmContact (Name of person)

    I then want to create a model view for each Application collection that shows:
    What applications the collection consists of.
    What dependencies there are between the applications in the collection and to applications outside the collection.
    What servers the applications run on
    What PhysicalHardware the servers run on (physical or a vmware)

    Is this possible using Archi?
    I can’t see a way to add more properties to a device. Is it not possible?
    Regards
    Terje</documentation>
